00:58:06.320 --> 00:58:11.390
So do you see any supernatural
aspect or evidence

00:58:11.390 --> 00:58:15.830
to the universe, and,
if so, how would it look

00:58:15.830 --> 00:58:18.670
different, absent that aspect?

00:58:22.250 --> 00:58:26.090
I think my religion informs my
way of looking at the universe,

00:58:26.090 --> 00:58:30.800
but it doesn't define
it or control it.

00:58:30.800 --> 00:58:33.830
It rather explains why
I'm interested in looking

00:58:33.830 --> 00:58:35.850
in the universe in
the first place.

00:58:35.850 --> 00:58:37.100
It doesn't tell me what to do.

00:58:37.100 --> 00:58:40.980
It tells me why
I want to do it--

00:58:40.980 --> 00:58:46.080
the fact that I find astronomy,
not only rational, but also

00:58:46.080 --> 00:58:51.597
fun, that I find
the ability to guess

00:58:51.597 --> 00:58:53.430
that this theory is
better than that theory,

00:58:53.430 --> 00:58:55.680
because it's more beautiful.

00:58:55.680 --> 00:59:00.270
To me, those are reflections
of the nature of the Creator.

00:59:00.270 --> 00:59:02.002
And that's very
different from saying,

00:59:02.002 --> 00:59:03.960
it must have been this
way, because I know God,

00:59:03.960 --> 00:59:05.850
and God would have
done it that way.

00:59:05.850 --> 00:59:07.140
That doesn't work.

00:59:07.140 --> 00:59:08.670
Because I don't
know God that well.

00:59:08.670 --> 00:59:09.820
I can't get away with that.

00:59:15.972 --> 00:59:17.420
Excuse me.

00:59:17.420 --> 00:59:21.410
I'm just dying to know, what
did you tell the woman--

00:59:21.410 --> 00:59:25.040
the Indian woman
who said, which sky?

00:59:25.040 --> 00:59:26.410
What did you tell her?

00:59:29.269 --> 00:59:31.310
I don't remember-- probably
something like that's

00:59:31.310 --> 00:59:32.206
a wonderful question.

00:59:39.180 --> 00:59:40.944
It is that I don't
know how to answer it.

00:59:40.944 --> 00:59:42.360
And if you were
to ask it today, I

00:59:42.360 --> 00:59:43.651
wouldn't know how to answer it.

00:59:50.441 --> 00:59:50.940
Here we go.

00:59:53.910 --> 00:59:56.710
A fascinating lecture--
what I gather from this

00:59:56.710 --> 01:00:02.320
is that you view all
cosmologies as transient.

01:00:02.320 --> 01:00:04.780
All of science is
transient, in the fact

01:00:04.780 --> 01:00:07.060
that a thousand years from
now, the science books

01:00:07.060 --> 01:00:09.580
are going to look real different
from the way they are now.

01:00:09.580 --> 01:00:13.330
But where we are now is
a necessary place to be,

01:00:13.330 --> 01:00:15.720
to get to where we're going
to be in a thousand years.

01:00:15.720 --> 01:00:18.100
Oh, good segue.

01:00:18.100 --> 01:00:19.475
I wanted to ask you a question.

01:00:19.475 --> 01:00:20.980
Oh, OK, sure.

01:00:20.980 --> 01:00:22.270
We'll get to that.

01:00:22.270 --> 01:00:27.310
How will we recognize
in the public, us,

01:00:27.310 --> 01:00:34.110
people in the audience, when
a new cosmology is rising,

01:00:34.110 --> 01:00:36.220
and how do we test it?

01:00:36.220 --> 01:00:39.100
In the public it's really hard.

01:00:39.100 --> 01:00:42.580
The trouble is that the things
that get reported in the news

01:00:42.580 --> 01:00:48.790
are new, and by their
nature, they're uncertain.

01:00:48.790 --> 01:00:50.770
People have done
studies of science

01:00:50.770 --> 01:00:52.960
as it's covered
in the newspapers.

01:00:52.960 --> 01:00:56.770
And it's generally
wildly inaccurate,

01:00:56.770 --> 01:00:59.800
not because of any
fault of the reporters,

01:00:59.800 --> 01:01:02.350
but because the new
stuff itself turns out

01:01:02.350 --> 01:01:03.430
to be wildly inaccurate--

01:01:03.430 --> 01:01:07.330
50% wrong, and we didn't
know yet where the 50% was.

01:01:07.330 --> 01:01:15.250
So my sense is to allow yourself
to be entertained by new ideas.

01:01:15.250 --> 01:01:19.050
But don't sell
your soul to them.

01:01:19.050 --> 01:01:22.980
Essentially, it takes about
a generation for an idea

01:01:22.980 --> 01:01:25.054
to become well
enough established,

01:01:25.054 --> 01:01:26.470
that you can have
some confidence,

01:01:26.470 --> 01:01:30.300
that it's a sure stepping
stone to go further.

01:01:30.300 --> 01:01:34.650
And science does
proceed rather slowly.

01:01:34.650 --> 01:01:39.420
There is a consensus effect
when a lot of scientists

01:01:39.420 --> 01:01:42.390
think that we can get
someplace with this.

01:01:42.390 --> 01:01:46.880
But there's also the sense
of, does it bear fruit?

01:01:46.880 --> 01:01:49.230
Do new, good ideas
come out of it,

01:01:49.230 --> 01:01:52.050
that we wouldn't have had
before, that explain things,

01:01:52.050 --> 01:01:55.500
maybe we didn't even know
needed explaining before?

01:01:55.500 --> 01:01:57.690
And that's why things
like string theory

01:01:57.690 --> 01:02:00.150
are so suspect,
because the string

01:02:00.150 --> 01:02:03.580
theorists seem to have run into
a brick wall at the moment.

01:02:03.580 --> 01:02:06.420
There was a guy in our
community, a Jesuit from Italy,

01:02:06.420 --> 01:02:07.560
who's doing string theory.

01:02:07.560 --> 01:02:10.020
And he's as
frustrated as anyone.

01:02:10.020 --> 01:02:13.020
But it could be-- you want
to give the next breakthrough

01:02:13.020 --> 01:02:13.830
around the road.

01:02:13.830 --> 01:02:15.330
You don't want to
give up on it yet.

01:02:15.330 --> 01:02:18.800
It's still one of the best
things we've got going.

01:02:18.800 --> 01:02:21.260
But there are a lot of
places where we're stuck.

01:02:21.260 --> 01:02:23.220
This stuff is hard.

01:02:23.220 --> 01:02:25.310
One of the things
that I worry about--

01:02:25.310 --> 01:02:27.710
and I've mentioned the
unspoken assumptions.

01:02:27.710 --> 01:02:29.480
We have a generation.

01:02:29.480 --> 01:02:33.740
We have how many generations
of physics students who

01:02:33.740 --> 01:02:36.230
have been educated
in our universities,

01:02:36.230 --> 01:02:40.490
since the advent of quantum
theory, since the realization

01:02:40.490 --> 01:02:43.760
that Newtonian physics
is fundamentally untrue?

01:02:43.760 --> 01:02:45.710
And, yet, how do we teach them?

01:02:45.710 --> 01:02:48.690
We teach them Newtonian physics.

01:02:48.690 --> 01:02:50.504
And there's a lot of
practical reasons.

01:02:50.504 --> 01:02:52.670
It allows you to build
bridges that don't fall down.

01:02:52.670 --> 01:02:54.003
You can get a job with it.

01:02:56.580 --> 01:03:00.170
But when it comes to
trying to understand

01:03:00.170 --> 01:03:03.650
the nature of physics
in physical reality,

01:03:03.650 --> 01:03:07.920
are we doing our students a
disservice by getting them

01:03:07.920 --> 01:03:11.781
to go think in the habit
of Newtonian physics,

01:03:11.781 --> 01:03:14.280
when, in fact, maybe those are
the wrong habits to think in?

01:03:14.280 --> 01:03:18.836
And, yet, how would you teach
a 17-year-old quantum physics,

01:03:18.836 --> 01:03:20.710
without teaching him
Newtonian physics first?

01:03:20.710 --> 01:03:24.140
We haven't figured that out yet.

01:03:24.140 --> 01:03:28.060
So we've got a long way to go.

01:03:28.060 --> 01:03:29.500
And that's why it's so much fun.

